{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:03:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:03:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18359"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18359"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.64,0.02,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74667"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11077"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60150"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25693"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25841"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe two major arteries in the leg are the posterior and anterior tibial arteries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries gives rise to these two vessels?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral artery","Popliteal artery","Internal iliac artery","Obturator artery","Inferior gluteal artery"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior tibial artery and anterior tibial artery are branches of the \u003Cstrong\u003Epopliteal artery\u003C/strong\u003E. The popliteal artery is a continuation of the femoral artery and runs through the popliteal fossa at the back of the knee. It then bifurcates into the anterior and posterior tibial arteries, which supply blood to the lower leg and foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the main artery supplying the thigh and continues as the popliteal artery after passing through the adductor hiatus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal iliac artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the pelvic organs and does not directly contribute to the blood supply of the lower leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the internal iliac artery and supplies the medial compartment of the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior gluteal artery\u003C/strong\u003E is another branch of the internal iliac artery, supplying the gluteal region.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The posterior tibial artery and anterior tibial artery are branches of the popliteal artery.","Understanding the vascular anatomy of the lower limb is crucial for diagnosing and managing peripheral vascular diseases."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60150"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18359"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60150"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T15:13:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T15:13:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11077"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74667"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10: